Nvidia Corporation was founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem in Santa Clara, California. Initially focused on graphics processing units (GPUs) for gaming and multimedia, Nvidia made a major breakthrough in 1999 with the release of the GeForce 256, marketed as the world’s first GPU. This innovation revolutionized computer graphics and established Nvidia as a leader in the industry.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia expanded its product line, acquiring key companies like 3dfx and later Mellanox in 2019 to enhance its capabilities in high-performance computing and data center technologies. The company also developed CUDA in 2006, a parallel computing platform that enabled GPUs to be used for general-purpose computing, significantly influencing AI and scientific research.

In the 2010s, Nvidia pivoted strongly toward AI, autonomous vehicles, and deep learning, with its GPUs becoming essential tools for machine learning tasks. Products like the Tesla and later the A100 GPU helped cement Nvidia’s role in powering AI workloads across industries.

In 2020, Nvidia announced plans to acquire ARM Holdings, although the deal was ultimately canceled in 2022 due to regulatory issues. Despite this, Nvidia continued its growth, becoming one of the most valuable semiconductor companies globally, especially as demand for AI and data center solutions surged.

Now recognized not just for gaming GPUs but also as a central force in artificial intelligence and computing innovation, Nvidia remains at the forefront of shaping modern technology.

claude
